ndinavian: topographic name for someone who lived by a conspicuous lime tree, Middle High German, Dutch <i>linde</i>, Scandinavian <i>lind</i>. There are several places, especially in northern Germany, named with this word, and the name may be a habitational name from any of these. The word was also used in a number of Old High German women's personal names, with the meaning ‘shield’ or ‘spear’ (these being made from the hard wood of the lime); it is possible that the surname in some cases is from a short form of one of these. As a Swedish name it is often ornamental rather than topographic. Compare   Lindy  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): adoption of German <i>Linde</i> ‘lime tree’ (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Fastre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Luis, Cesar, Juan, Joaquin, Manuel, Alfonso, Anselmo, Armando, Carlos, Domingo, Enrique, Fernando.","Catalan and Spanish: occupational name from <i>sastre</i> ‘tailor’ (from Latin <i>sartor</i>)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Fastre De Ligne was born about 1180, in Ligne, Ath, Hainaut, Belgium, his father, Thierry II de Ligne, was 51 and his mother, Elisabeth d'Antoing, was 37. He had at least 1 daughter with Brigitte van Gavre. He died about 1246, at the age of 68."},"et":{"about 1180–about 1246":"umbes 1180–umbes 1246","1180–1246":"1180–1246","–Male":"Surnud","1192–Female":"1192–Surnud","1210–1274":"1210–1274","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","1190":"1190","1246":"1246","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1145":"1145","1210":"1210","about 1246":"umbes 1246","1274":"1274","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","about 1210":"umbes 1210","1192":"1192","1180":"1180","Ligne, Ath, Hainaut, Belgium":"Ligne, Ath, Hainaut, Belgia"},"fi":{"about 1180–a